{
  "id": "phekb-resistant-hypertension-comprehensive",
  "source": "phekb",
  "source_id": "resistant-hypertension",
  "name": "Resistant Hypertension - Comprehensive Provider Query (Multi-Resource)",
  "description": "Provider-level query identifying resistant HTN via the full PheKB algorithm — Condition (resistant HTN dx) + MedicationRequest (4 antihypertensive classes) + Observation (SBP >140). Mirrors both Type-1 (>=4 meds) and Type-2 (3 meds + uncontrolled BP) PheKB criteria.",
  "prompt": "I need to identify all patients with resistant hypertension for a cardiology quality program. Some have a coded resistant HTN diagnosis. Others are on >=3 antihypertensive medications with persistently elevated SBP >140 (suggesting Type-2 resistant HTN per the eMERGE algorithm) without a formal diagnosis. Run multiple FHIR queries — diagnosis, antihypertensives, and elevated SBP — and union the patient sets.",
  "prompts": {
    "naive": "Find all resistant HTN patients.",
    "broad": "Find resistant HTN patients — by diagnosis, by 4-class antihypertensive regimens (lisinopril, amlodipine, HCTZ, spironolactone), or by elevated SBP >140 mmHg. Run multiple queries and union.",
    "expert": "I need to identify resistant hypertension patients using the full PheKB eMERGE algorithm, which requires evidence across three resource types. First, search Condition resources for a documented resistant hypertensive disorder diagnosis (coded in SNOMED CT). Second, search MedicationRequest resources for prescriptions covering the four major antihypertensive drug classes used in resistant HTN regimens — an ACE inhibitor (lisinopril), a calcium channel blocker (amlodipine), a thiazide diuretic (hydrochlorothiazide), and an aldosterone antagonist (spironolactone), all coded in RxNorm. Third, search Observation resources for systolic blood pressure readings — coded via LOINC — that exceed one hundred forty mmHg, which defines uncontrolled blood pressure under the PheKB Type-2 criterion. Union the patient sets from all three queries to capture both Type-1 resistant HTN (polypharmacy pathway) and Type-2 (elevated BP despite three-drug therapy)."
  },
